        <a href="/tech/">Technology</a>
        </h2></legend>
        <div class="row"><div class="column vcwi"><div itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/NewsArticle" class="card">
  <meta itemprop="datePublished" content="Tue, 21 Jul 2026 16:00:00 GMT">
  <meta itemprop="dateModified" content="Tue, 21 Jul 2026 16:00:00 GMT">
  <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
    <meta itemprop="name" content="Enrique Dans, Fast Company">
  </span>
  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="image" role="presentation">
      <img src="/static15/tech/2026/07/21/next-enterprise-ai-frontier-is-the-optimizable-company.webp" alt="The next enterprise AI frontier is the optimizable company" itemprop="image" width="400" height="225"
        onerror="this.parentNode.style.display='none'" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" loading="lazy">
    </div>
    <h3 itemprop="headline">The next enterprise AI frontier is the optimizable company</h3>
    <p itemprop="text">
      For the past two years, companies have been trying to add AI to their processes. That sounded reasonable at first. Existing workflows, existing systems, existing data, existing dashboards — now with intelligence attached.
